SIMPLE: room
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Room
<hw>Room</hw> <pr>(r⟦oomac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>roum</ets>, <ets>rum</ets>, space, AS. <ets>r⟦umac⟧m</ets>; akin to
OS., OFries. & Icel. <ets>r⟦umac⟧m</ets>, D. <ets>ruim</ets>, G.
<ets>raum</ets>, OHG. <ets>r⟦umac⟧m</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>rum</ets>,
Goth. <ets>r⟦umac⟧ms</ets>, and to AS. <ets>r⟦umac⟧m</ets>, adj.,
spacious, D. <ets>ruim</ets>, Icel. <ets>r⟦umac⟧mr</ets>, Goth.
<ets>r⟦umac⟧ms</ets>; and prob. to L. <ets>rus</ets> country (cf.
<er>Rural</er>), Zend <ets>rava⟦ndot⟧h</ets> wide, free, open,
<ets>ravan</ets> a plain.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Unobstructed spase;
space which may be occupied by or devoted to any object; compass; extent
of place, great or small; <as>as, there is not <ex>room</ex> for a
house; the table takes up too much <ex>room</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord, it is done as thou hast commanded, and yet there is
<qex>room</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xiv. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was no <qex>room</qex> for them in the inn.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke ii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A particular portion of space appropriated for
occupancy; a place to sit, stand, or lie; a seat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he have but twelve pence in his purse, he will give it for the
best <qex>room</qex> in a playhouse.</q>
<rj><qau>Overbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When thou art bidden of any man to a wedding, sit not down in the
highest <qex>room</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xiv. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Especially, space in a building or ship inclosed or
set apart by a partition; an apartment or chamber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I found the prince in the next <qex>room</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Place or position in society; office; rank; post;
station; also, a place or station once belonging to, or occupied by,
another, and vacated.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he heard that Archelaus did reign in Judea in the
<qex>room</qex> of his father Herod.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. ii.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither that I look for a higher <qex>room</qex> in heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let Bianca take her sister's <qex>room</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Possibility of admission; ability to admit;
opportunity to act; fit occasion; <as>as, to leave <ex>room</ex> for
hope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was no prince in the empire who had <qex>room</qex> for such
an alliance.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Room and space</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>,
<cd>the distance from one side of a rib to the corresponding side of the
next rib; <xex>space</xex> being the distance between two ribs, in the
clear, and <xex>room</xex> the width of a rib.</cd> -- <col><b>To give
room</b></col>, <cd>to withdraw; to leave or provide space unoccupied
for others to pass or to be seated.</cd> -- <col><b>To make
room</b></col>, <cd>to open a space, way, or passage; to remove
obstructions; to give room.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Make room</qex>, and let him stand before our face.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Space; compass; scope; latitude.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Room</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Room
<hw>Room</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Roomed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rooming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To occupy a room or rooms; to
lodge; <as>as, they arranged to <ex>room</ex> together</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Room</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Room
<hw>Room</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>r⟦umac⟧m</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Spacious; roomy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No <qex>roomer</qex> harbour in the place.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roomage</ent>⟦br⟧
